        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity:
The CASA simulations using the C34-6 array configuration suggested by ALMA-OT yield a synthesized beam of 0.27". This resolution is adequate to resolve the accretion zone (0.014 pc in diameter for a mass of 500 Msun or 0.5" at a distance of 6kpc)  within the gravitational radius. We request a sensitivity of 1.2 mJy  (or 0.3 K) theoretical rms thermal noise level (assuming the default 1.26 PWV weather conditions), with the (smoothed) 1.3 km/s velocity resolution. The SMA observations toward G10.6-0.4 have detected bright H30alpha (peak of 80 K) emission with a ~30 km/s in FWHM. The requested sensitivity and velocity resolution are sufficient to differentiate the accelerated rotation/infall, and faint ionized outflow.  The 0.3 K sensitivity will detect the CH3OH and CH3CN lines with &gt; 20 sigma significance based on the spectra from our SMA observations.

Correlator setup:
We will observe with four 1875 MHz BW based bands, to cover the proposed H30alpha line and the molecular gas tracers CH3OH and CH3CN J=12-11. The maximized total bandwidth will simultaneously yield a deep 1.3 mm dust continuum image. Spectral lines are wide spread in all four base bands for G10.6. We request visibility data be saved in full spectral resolution.


Imaging requirements:
We used the high resolution VLA 1.3 cm continuum image as the sky model to simulate the C34-6 configuration  observations at the frequency of 231 GHz. We found that with the total observing time, we can achieve a spatial dynamic range of &gt; 100. At the channel which the H30alpha line peaks, this spatial dynamic range will yield an rms noise close to the theoretical thermal noise level. The existing SMA observations of the proposed spectral lines are sensitive to the angular scale of 0.63-22" (i.e. 6-393 kilo lambda), which will serve as the short-spacing database to further improve the spatial dynamic range. The compact continuum source of our target will enable self-calibrations.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
