    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Massive protostars must accrete 40 to 60 Msun to become O stars, but they begin core hydrogen burning well before reaching their final masses. At a stage equivalent of a B0 star, the surface temperature is high enough to create a significant HII region around the star. This poses an interesting theoretical question: How does accretion proceeds through the pressure differential between the cold molecular and hot ionized gas? This ALMA proposal aims at imaging both molecular and ionized gas at high angular resolution and high sensitivity to investigate the molecular and ionized accretion as well as ionized outflow in a protocluster forming HII region G10.6-0.4.The new data will test the theoretical model that we developed on ionized accretion.

</prp:abstract>
